兜塚古墳 (仙台市)
{{Infobox ancient site|type = {{ill|scallop-shaped kofun|ja|帆立貝形古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/scallop-shaped kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}| name = Kabutozuka Kofun| image =File:Kabutozuka-kofun 2005-07.jpg| caption = July 2005| location = [[:en:Miyagi Prefecture|Miyagi Prefecture]][[:en:Sendai|Sendai]][[:en:Taihaku-ku, Sendai|Taihaku Ward]], Negishimachi 14| coordinates = {{Coord|38.238667|N|140.884222|E|region:JP_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | map = JP| type = [[:en:Zenpokoenfun|Zenpokoenfun]]| built = Late [[:en:5th century|5th century]]| burial =| map_size = Approx. 75 [[:en:Metre|meters]] long| Buried individual =| excavations =| Historic Site Historic Site =| notes =| architectural_styles = {{ill|keyhole-shaped kofun|qid=Q11268718|1=Zenpokoenfun|2=ja|3=前方後円墳|4=ko|5=전방후원분|6=zh|7=前方後圓墳}}}}'''Kabutozuka Kofun''' (兜塚古墳) is a [[:en:Kofun|Kofun]] located on the grounds of the present-day {{ill|Miyagi Prefectural Sendai Minami High School|ja|宮城県仙台南高等学校|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyagi Prefectural Sendai Minami High School|qq=|1=Miyagi Prefectural Sendai Minami High School|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11453655}} in [[:en:Miyagi Prefecture|Miyagi Prefecture]], [[:en:Sendai|Sendai]], [[:en:Taihaku-ku, Sendai|Taihaku Ward]]. It is a scallop-shaped [[:en:Zenpokoenfun|Zenpokoenfun]] estimated to have been constructed in the late [[:en:5th century|5th century]]. Measuring approximately 75 [[:en:Metre|meters]] in total length, it features [[:en:Fukiishi|fukiishi]] and [[:en:Haniwa|haniwa]], making it one of the largest tumuli in the Sendai Plain during its era.
== location and burial == Kabutozuka Kofun is situated on the southern (right) bank of the {{ill|Hirose River (Miyagi)|ja|広瀬川 (宮城県)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hirose River (Miyagi)|qq=|1=Hirose River|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11485581}} in the alluvial plain at the eastern foot of {{ill|Ōtoshiyama|ja|大年寺山|1=Mount Daidenji|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtoshiyama|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Daidenji|qq=}}. Several smaller tumuli, such as {{ill|Hitotsuka Kofun|ja|一塚古墳|1=Hitotsuka Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hitotsuka Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Hitotsuka Kofun|qq=}}, {{ill|Futatsuka Kofun (Sendai)|ja|二塚古墳 (仙台市)|1=Futatsuzuka Kofun (Sendai)|lt=Futatsuzuka Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Futatsuka Kofun (Sendai)|13=User:Immanuelle/Futatsuzuka Kofun (Sendai)|qq=}}, and {{ill|Uramachi Kofun|ja|裏町古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Uramachi Kofun|qq=}}, are located in similar settings. The nearby {{ill|Ōnodera Kofun Group|ja|大野田古墳群|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōnodera Kofun Group|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, smaller in map_size, consists of a denser cluster of tumuli. The interred individuals in Kabutozuka Kofun and similar sites are thought to belong to a higher-Ranking leadership class compared to those buried in the Ōnodera group<ref>‘Sendai City History’, Special Edition (Archaeological Materials), "Ōnodera Kofun Group," p. 260.</ref>.The tumulus currently appears as a circular mound approximately 50 meters in diameter due to the truncation of the front section by the Kabutozuka Line municipal road<ref>Sendai Municipal Road Taihaku 385 (Kabutozuka Line), minimum width 7.80 m, maximum width 12.00 m, length 483.2 m.</ref>. Its original area are estimated as follows: a posterior circular section 62.4 meters in diameter, a 15-meter-long anterior section, an overall axial length of approximately 75 meters, a width of 30 meters at the front end of the anterior section, and a height of 6.8 meters in the posterior section. The surrounding moat is about 13 meters wide near the posterior section<ref name="#1">‘Sendai City History’, Special Edition (Archaeological Materials), "Kabutozuka Kofun," p. 256.</ref>. The tumulus is of a scallop-shaped design with a notably small anterior section.The posterior section appears to have two tiers clearly visible to the naked eye, with the possibility of three or more tiers. The mound's stepped appearance is thought to have inspired its name, likened to an inverted kabuto (helmet). The slopes of these tiers were covered with [[:en:Fukiishi|fukiishi]], and cylindrical and morning glory-shaped [[:en:Haniwa|haniwa]] were arranged along the tiers.
